53
00:04:26,200 --> 00:04:28,700
- You could have killed him, couldn't you?
- <i>Hai.</i>

54
00:04:28,800 --> 00:04:30,200
Why didn't you then?

55
00:04:30,300 --> 00:04:34,100
<i>Because, Daniel</i>-san<i>,</i>
<i>for person with no forgiveness in heart...</i>

56
00:04:34,200 --> 00:04:37,100
<i>... living even worse punishment</i>
<i>than death.</i>

57
00:05:41,700 --> 00:05:45,800
Sensei <i>Kreese, this is Pat Johnson</i>
<i>from the All Valley Tournament.</i>

58
00:05:45,900 --> 00:05:47,900
<i>We're sorry you lost all your students.</i>

59
00:05:47,900 --> 00:05:50,900
<i>I guess the Cobra Kai won't</i>
<i>enter the tournament this year.</i>

60
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:53,700
<i>We've made repeated requests</i>
<i>for payments of dues...</i>

61
00:05:53,700 --> 00:05:56,000
<i>... but since you've failed to respond...</i>

62
00:05:56,100 --> 00:05:59,300
<i>... we have to drop the Cobra Kai</i>
<i>from our membership rolls.</i>

63
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:02,500
<i>If you have any questions, give me a call.</i>
<i>Have a nice day.</i>

64
00:06:02,600 --> 00:06:04,400
<i>Mr. Kreese, this is Pacific Bell.</i>

65
00:06:04,500 --> 00:06:08,700
<i>This is the final call regarding your bill,</i>
<i>and if you do not pay immediately...</i>

66
00:06:20,800 --> 00:06:24,400
Mr. Kreese, good morning.
What a surprise. Some coffee?

67
00:06:24,900 --> 00:06:27,100
- Where's the boss?
- He's upstairs.

68
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:28,400
Thanks.

69
00:07:08,300 --> 00:07:09,400
Come on!

70
00:07:17,800 --> 00:07:20,100
You're telegraphing that wheel kick.

71
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:23,500
Johnny!

72
00:07:24,400 --> 00:07:25,900
What a surprise, man!

73
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:27,200
Yes!

74
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:30,600
What's this? You moving in?

75
00:07:30,700 --> 00:07:33,300
This is "I give up." I came to say good-bye.

76
00:07:33,400 --> 00:07:35,900
- Here are the <i>dojo</i> keys.
- What are you talking about?

77
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:37,600
I'll pay you that back rent soon.

78
00:07:37,700 --> 00:07:40,800
You think I bought that place for the rent?
I bought it for you.

79
00:07:40,900 --> 00:07:42,100
- Mr. Silver?
- What?

80
00:07:42,100 --> 00:07:43,700
The plutonium deal.

81
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:47,100
Johnny, every business has a slump
at one time or another.

82
00:07:47,100 --> 00:07:49,600
Ten years ago
nuclear was the preferred waste.

83
00:07:49,600 --> 00:07:52,500
You could dump it anywhere.
Now, everybody's a detective.

84
00:07:52,600 --> 00:07:55,500
I'm lucky if I make one deal a year
without being indicted.

85
00:07:55,600 --> 00:07:56,600
Thank you.

86
00:07:56,700 --> 00:07:57,900
Let's get some air.

87
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:01,000
It's been nine months since a student
walked through my doors.

88
00:08:01,100 --> 00:08:03,900
You're not listening to me.
Come on, snap out of it.

89
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:05,200
I can't.

90
00:08:05,700 --> 00:08:08,100
I'm broke and I'm going nowhere.

91
00:08:09,400 --> 00:08:10,600
You're wrong.

92
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:13,100
You're going to Tahiti.

93
00:08:13,500 --> 00:08:14,200
Now.

94
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,100
All right, I've made up my mind.

95
00:08:17,200 --> 00:08:19,600
This slope, Miyagi, and that punk kid...

96
00:08:19,600 --> 00:08:21,600
...I'll get them for what they did to you.

97
00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:24,000
They made you suffer,
so I'll make them suffer.

98
00:08:25,100 --> 00:08:28,600
When I think they've suffered enough,
then I start with the pain.

99
00:08:28,700 --> 00:08:32,200
- Terry, you don't have to do that.
- Don't have to? I want to.

100
00:08:32,300 --> 00:08:34,400
It's not over. We're Cobra Kai.

101
00:08:34,800 --> 00:08:37,400
Come on, say it. Cobra Kai.

102
00:08:38,100 --> 00:08:40,400
Say it! Cobra Kai.

103
00:08:40,500 --> 00:08:42,800
- Never dies.
- You bet your ass.

104
00:08:42,900 --> 00:08:45,000
- I owe you, man.
- You don't owe me anything.

105
00:08:45,100 --> 00:08:47,800
I don't owe you anything?
What about Vietnam?

106
00:08:47,900 --> 00:08:49,900
How many times did you save my ass?

107
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:52,700
I don't know. I lost count.

108
00:08:54,900 --> 00:08:56,600
Get the hell out of here.

109
00:09:01,100 --> 00:09:02,900
Have a good trip, Captain.

110
00:09:10,200 --> 00:09:14,900
<i>The White Zone is for the immediate</i>
<i>loading and unloading of passengers only.</i>

111
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:17,200
Smog.

112
00:09:17,300 --> 00:09:19,600
Smells like home, huh, Mr. Miyagi?

113
00:09:21,700 --> 00:09:25,400
Daniel-<i>san</i>,
why mother not here to meet you?

114
00:09:25,500 --> 00:09:27,500
You tell her right flight number?

115
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:30,500
I told her the right flight.
I just told her the wrong day.

116
00:09:30,500 --> 00:09:33,900
I told her we were coming in tomorrow.
She loves surprises.

117
00:09:34,400 --> 00:09:35,400
Hope so.

118
00:09:35,500 --> 00:09:40,000
We take taxi apartment house.
Then Miyagi go back to work.

119
00:09:41,600 --> 00:09:43,800
<i>106 Los Angeles. Crank it up!</i>

120
00:10:08,300 --> 00:10:10,200
What are you doing in my cab?

121
00:10:10,300 --> 00:10:13,700
- We just came from the airport.
- I thought that was the cab I ordered.

122
00:10:13,800 --> 00:10:16,700
- Mrs. Milo, what's going on?
- What does it seem? Progress.

123
00:10:16,800 --> 00:10:19,100
I got a message for you from your mother.

124
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:24,600
I told you that bum would sell the place
and you'd be out of a job someday.

125
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:26,500
You wouldn't listen to me.

126
00:10:26,600 --> 00:10:28,100
- What's the message?
- What message?

127
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:31,600
- The one from my mother.
- She said call her at your Uncle Louie's.

128
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:35,900
No worry nothing, Mrs. LaRusso.

129
00:10:37,300 --> 00:10:39,600
Daniel-<i>san</i> room all finished.

130
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:44,200
Yeah, I take good care of him.
You just look out Uncle Louie.

131
00:10:44,400 --> 00:10:46,900
I might be here for a few months.

132
00:10:47,100 --> 00:10:50,800
A 70-year-old man gets emphysema,
it's no joke, you know.

133
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:54,700
Are you sure there's no problem
for him to stay with you?

134
00:10:54,700 --> 00:10:56,200
No problem.

135
00:10:56,300 --> 00:10:57,400
Pleasure.

136
00:10:57,500 --> 00:10:59,100
<i>Mr. Miyagi, thank you.</i>

137
00:10:59,500 --> 00:11:03,000
Welcome. Bye-bye. Here Daniel-<i>san</i>.

138
00:11:03,400 --> 00:11:04,500
Nice mama.

139
00:11:05,100 --> 00:11:06,900
You sure you don't need me there?

140
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,000
<i>No. You stay with Mr. Miyagi</i>
<i>and start college.</i>

141
00:11:10,500 --> 00:11:14,700
I can't believe it, "Mr. College Man."
When's registration?

142
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:17,100
<i>It's this Tuesday.</i>
<i>And classes start Thursday.</i>

143
00:11:17,200 --> 00:11:19,100
And when is Kumiko arriving?

144
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:22,100
She's not.

145
00:11:22,200 --> 00:11:26,700
She got this great job
with a dance company in Tokyo.

146
00:11:26,800 --> 00:11:29,200
I guess she just couldn't say no, so...

147
00:11:30,700 --> 00:11:32,200
You're disappointed, huh?

148
00:11:32,800 --> 00:11:36,200
Yep. But that's life, I guess.
I'll survive.

149
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:38,400
You'll do more than just survive.

150
00:11:39,800 --> 00:11:41,400
I gotta go, okay?

151
00:11:41,500 --> 00:11:43,900
Listen, Uncle Louie says hi,
and I love you.

152
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:46,700
Okay, say hi to Uncle Louie.
I love you, too.

153
00:11:55,900 --> 00:11:58,400
The little maple's still in there.
I'll get it.

154
00:11:58,500 --> 00:12:00,400
No. I go.

155
00:12:41,700 --> 00:12:43,500
Mr. Miyagi, you okay?

156
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:53,200
Just remembering.

157
00:12:57,600 --> 00:13:00,500
I'll bet there are a lot of memories
here for you.

158
00:13:05,100 --> 00:13:07,200
So what are you going to do now?

159
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:12,200
Don't know.

160
00:13:14,200 --> 00:13:17,300
Well, did you ever think about
opening a <i>bonsai</i> store?

161
00:13:20,400 --> 00:13:22,100
<i>Hai</i>, Daniel-<i>san</i>.

162
00:13:22,700 --> 00:13:24,200
In my dream.

163
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:26,600
My retirement.

164
00:13:29,800 --> 00:13:31,400
What do you call this?

165
00:13:38,400 --> 00:13:39,900
Call "time to go."

166
00:14:06,600 --> 00:14:09,900
You know, I've been thinking about
the <i>bonsai</i> shop idea.

167
00:14:10,100 --> 00:14:13,100
